solutions.content:
# Approach
- There are two approaches to this question - one with a numerical variable that stores the current bit values and the other one is a string variable that stores the bit values at a particular leaf node.
- The problem with the numerical variable is that, there's a limit to how many bit values it can store and thus gives an error after the critical value. Hence we use the String variable to record the bit values.
- The problem is divided into two classes - main and helper

# Global Variables
- number (String type)
- arr (Arraylist String type)

# Helper Class
- The helper class takes a node as an input
- if node is null, returns to the parent node
- adds the node bit value to number
- checks if the node is leaf node, if yes, the current number value is appended in arr
- calls itself on current node left child
- calls itself on current node right child
- deletes the last character of number

# Main class
- calls the helper class on root node
- arr is created and full of leaf node bit values but in string format
- create int variable sum = 0
- set a for loop to iterate thorugh the array
- convert each string bit value to integer and add it to the sum.
- return sum

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(V) V  is the number of nodes

- Space complexity: O(L) L is the number of leaf nodes

# Code
```

/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * public class TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode left;
 *     TreeNode right;
 *     TreeNode() {}
 *     TreeNode(int val) { this.val = val; }
 *     TreeNode(int val, TreeNode left, TreeNode right) {
 *         this.val = val;
 *         this.left = left;
 *         this.right = right;
 *     }
 * }
 */
class Solution {

    public String number = "";

    public List<String> arr = new ArrayList<>();

    public int sumRootToLeaf(TreeNode root) {
        tree(root);
        int sum = 0;
        for(String i: arr){
            int a = Integer.parseInt(i, 2);
            System.out.println(a);
            sum += a;
        }
        return sum;
    }

    public void tree(TreeNode x){
        if(x == null){
            return;
        }

        number = number + String.valueOf(x.val);

        if(x.left == null && x.right == null){
            arr.add(number);
        }

        tree(x.left);
        tree(x.right);

        number = number.substring(0,number.length()-1);

    }
}
```

