# PLEASE UPVOTE ME 🥹🥹

# Intuition
We want to find the largest path value in a directed graph, which means we need to find the longest path ending at each node.
We can use topological sorting to traverse the graph in a way that ensures we only visit nodes that have all their incoming edges processed.
At each visited node, we can update the counts for its neighbors based on the counts for the current node and the color of the neighbor.
We can use a set of nodes with zero indegrees to start the traversal and continue until we have visited all nodes, or detect a cycle in the graph.
The counts array allows us to keep track of the number of occurrences of each color in the longest path ending at each node, which is what we need to compute the largest path value.

# Approach
The problem asks to find the largest path value in a directed graph, where each node has a color from the range [a, z].
We can use topological sorting to traverse the graph and compute the count of each color in the longest path ending at each node.
To do this, we first build the adjacency list and the array of indegrees for each node, as well as a set of nodes with zero indegrees.
We also initialize an array of counts for each node and color, with counts[i][j] representing the number of occurrences of color j in the longest path ending at node i.
Then, we start traversing the graph from the nodes with zero indegrees, updating the counts for the neighbors of each visited node.
Finally, we return the maximum count among all nodes if we have visited all nodes, or -1 if there is a cycle in the graph.


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

  int largestPathValue(string colors, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        int n = colors.size();
        int k = 26;
        vector<int> indegrees(n, 0);
        vector<vector<int>> graph(n, vector<int>());
        for (vector<int>& edge : edges) {
            int u = edge[0];
            int v = edge[1];
            graph[u].push_back(v);
            indegrees[v]++;
        }
        unordered_set<int> zero_indegree;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (indegrees[i] == 0) {
                zero_indegree.insert(i);
            }
        }
        vector<vector<int>> counts(n, vector<int>(k, 0));
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            counts[i][colors[i] - 'a']++;
        }
        int max_count = 0;
        int visited = 0;
        while (!zero_indegree.empty()) {
            int u = *zero_indegree.begin();
            zero_indegree.erase(u);
            visited++;
            for (int v : graph[u]) {
                for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
                    counts[v][i] = max(counts[v][i], counts[u][i] + (colors[v] - 'a' == i ? 1 : 0));
                }
                indegrees[v]--;
                if (indegrees[v] == 0) {
                    zero_indegree.insert(v);
                }
            }
            max_count = max(max_count, *max_element(counts[u].begin(), counts[u].end()));
        }
        return visited == n ? max_count : -1;
    }

};
```

