# Intuition
I solve this question with BFS and 2D dynamic programming. the reason why I use 2D dynamic programming is that we need to keep track of two data. One is current location and the other is how many colors we have so far when we are at some point.

# Approach
1. Create an empty graph using defaultdict with lists as the default value to represent edges.

2. Create an array called indegree to keep track of the number of incoming edges for each vertex. Initialize each value to 0.

1. Iterate over each edge in the input edges list. If an edge has the same source and destination, return -1. Add the destination vertex to the list of edges for the source vertex in the graph dictionary. Increment the indegree of the destination vertex.

1. Create a queue called q and add all the vertices with 0 incoming edges (indegree) to the queue.

1. Create a 2D array called dp with dimensions (number of vertices x 26) to keep track of the largest color value for each color at each vertex. Initialize each value to 0.

1. Initialize a variable called max_color to 0 to keep track of the largest color value found so far.

1. While the queue is not empty, remove the vertex at the front of the queue and process it.

1. Get the color of the vertex from the input colors string by subtracting 'a' from the ASCII code of the character at that index. Increment the value at dp[vertex][color] by 1.

1. Update max_color to be the maximum value of dp[vertex][color] and max_color.

1. For each neighbor (nei) of the current vertex, decrement its indegree by 1. For each color (c), update dp[nei][c] to be the maximum of its current value and dp[vertex][c].

1. If the indegree of the neighbor becomes 0, add it to the queue.

1. If any vertex has a non-zero indegree, return -1.

1. Return the value of max_color.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(V + E)
V is the number of vertex (colors) and E is the number of edges in the graph. This is because we traverse the graph using BFS, visiting each node and each edge only once.

- Space complexity: O(VK + E)
V is the number of vertex in the graph, K is the number of possible colors (26 in this case), and E is the number of edges in the graph. This is because we create a 2D dp array of size V*K to store the count of each color at each node, and an adjacency list to represent the edges of the graph, which takes up O(E) space.

