# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
1. In a directed graph, a cycle is confirmed, if we are able to reach a node again in its dfs call itself. So keep this check to detect cycle.
2. As there are only 26 possible lowercase english alphabets, so we can safely try all ways via "dynamic programming" approach as the constraint is 10<sup>5</sup> for the no. of nodes, and for each node we can maintain state of 26 colors. So, overall state maintenance of O(26 X 10<sup>5</sup>) , which is feasible.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Let t[i][j] denote the max color in path starting from node 'i' of color (j-'a'). Here, if 'n' is the total no. of nodes (obtained from colors.size()), then 'i' belongs to [0,n-1] and 'j' belongs to [0,26].

2. It is possible that on path from some node 'u', we reach a node 'v' which has been already visited and finished earlier, so instead of computing again, use the state maintained in t[v][j] to compute the t[v's parent][j], for all j in [0,26-1] and return so on till t[u][j] is not computed for all j.

3. The cycle detection would need another visited array, but for marking the status of completeness of each node, we can make an extra entry in 't' table only as t[u][26] to denote -1 for not visited, 0 for visited, 1 for finished. Taking an extra visited array will be of same complexity as anyway equal no. of integer entries are stored, so equal bytes will be consumed.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The time taken will be O(26(|V|+|E|)) for the overall dfs and then O(26|V|) for initialisation and computing the final maximum from t.
Thus, O(26(|V|+|E|)).
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
For the adjacency list, O(|V|+|E|). And for the 't' table, it will be O(27|V|). Revursion stack space will be O(|V|+|E|).
Thus, O(max(27|V|, |V|+|E|)). 
# Code
```
class Solution {
    void dfs(string& colors,vector<int> adjlist[],int t[][27],int cur,bool& cycle){
        t[cur][26]=0;   //marked visited
        // bool leaf=true;
        for(auto neigh: adjlist[cur]){
            // leaf=false;
            if(t[neigh][26]==-1){
                //call dfs over it
                dfs(colors,adjlist,t,neigh,cycle);
                //check if cycle formed, then return -1 on priority
                if(cycle){
                    return;
                }
            }else{
                //check if t[neigh][26]!=-1 is due to a cycle or not
                //if the node is revisited in its own dfs call, then only a cycle, but if a finished node is revisited, then its not a cycle as some other starting vertex is calling dfs() over it
                if(t[neigh][26]==0){
                    cycle=true;
                    return;
                }
            }
            //if either the neighbor already visited or now call completed over it
            for(int i=0;i<26;i++){
                t[cur][i]=max(t[cur][i],t[neigh][i]);
            }
        }
        t[cur][colors[cur]-'a']+=1;     //since one more than all of its neighbors as it is of that particular character 
        //now we have computed t[cur][i] for all colors i
        //even if it was a leaf(sink), we have done +1 at last
        t[cur][26]=1;   //marked finished
        return;
    }
public:
    int largestPathValue(string colors, vector<vector<int>>& edges) {
        int n=colors.size();
        vector<int> adjlist[n];
        for(int i=0;i<edges.size();i++){
            adjlist[edges[i][0]].push_back(edges[i][1]);
        }
        int t[n][27];   //since colors is one of 26 lowercase alphabets
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<26;j++){
                t[i][j]=0;
            }
            t[i][26]=-1;        //this extra one to check visited or not, finished or not
        }
        bool cycle=false;   //assume no cycle initially
        //t[i][j]=max path length starting from node 'i' of color 'a'+j
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(t[i][26]==-1){
                //call dfs from this node
                dfs(colors,adjlist,t,i,cycle);
                if(cycle){
                    return -1;
                }
            }
        }
        //reached here means no cycle
        //return the maximum value found
        int ans=0;
        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            for(int j=0;j<26;j++){
                ans=max(ans,t[i][j]);
            }
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

