```
class Solution {

    public int largestPathValue(String colors, int[][] edges) {
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> graph = makeGraph(edges);
        int n = colors.length();
        // nodeStatus: 0 = unvisited, 1 = visiting, 2 = visited
        int[] nodeStatus = new int[n];
        Set<Character> allColors = new HashSet<>();
        for(char c : colors.toCharArray()) {
            allColors.add(c);
        }
        Map<Integer, Map<Character, Integer>> nodeToColorToVal = new HashMap<>();
        int max = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<n; i++) {
            if(nodeStatus[i] == 2) {
                continue;
            }
            int lcv = explore(i, graph, nodeStatus, colors, allColors, nodeToColorToVal);
            if (lcv == -1) {
                return -1;
            }
            max = Math.max(max, lcv);
        }
        return max;
    }

    // creates adjacency graph representation
    private Map<Integer, List<Integer>> makeGraph(int[][] edges) {
        Map<Integer, List<Integer>> graph = new HashMap<>();
        for(int[] edge : edges) {
            int from = edge[0];
            int to = edge[1];
            List<Integer> children = graph.getOrDefault(from, new ArrayList<>());
            children.add(to);
            graph.put(from, children);
        }
        return graph;
    }

    private Map<Character, Integer> initColorToVal(Set<Character> allColors) {
        Map<Character, Integer> map = new HashMap<>();
        for(Character c : allColors) {
            map.put(c, 0);
        }
        return map;
    }

    //return -1 if cycle
    private int explore(int node,
                        Map<Integer,
                        List<Integer>> graph,
                        int[] nodeStatus,
                        String colors,
                        Set<Character> allColors,
                        Map<Integer, Map<Character, Integer>> nodeToColorToVal) {
        // mark node as visiting
        nodeStatus[node] = 1;
        int max = 1;
        Map<Character, Integer> colorToVal = initColorToVal(allColors);

        // recurse children
        for(Integer child : graph.getOrDefault(node, new ArrayList<>())) {
            // found a back edge, that is, found a cycle
            if (nodeStatus[child] == 1) {
                return -1;
            }
            // only recurse if not visited
            if (nodeStatus[child] == 0) {
                int cVal = explore(child, graph, nodeStatus, colors, allColors, nodeToColorToVal);
                if (cVal == -1) {
                    return -1;
                }
            }
            // handle colorToVal business
            for(Character color : allColors) {
                int existingVal = colorToVal.get(color);
                int childVal = nodeToColorToVal.get(child).get(color);
                if (childVal > existingVal) {
                    colorToVal.put(color, childVal);
                    max = Math.max(max, childVal);
                }
            }
        }
        // and add contribution of current node to appropriate color
        int currCurrentVal = colorToVal.getOrDefault(colors.charAt(node), 0) + 1;
        colorToVal.put(colors.charAt(node), currCurrentVal);
        max = Math.max(max, currCurrentVal);

        // populate our collection of subproblems with that for this node
        nodeToColorToVal.put(node, colorToVal);
        // mark node as visited
        nodeStatus[node] = 2;
        return max;
    }

}
```
Explanation:
First let's make 2 observations about this problem:
1) If we have LCV along a path, then extending it can only improve the LCV. This suggests naive approach where, for all "roots" with no inbound edges, keep following paths till we hit a "leaf" with no outbound edges and find LCVs over each such trajectory and max over them. Simple DFS would find all root->leaf paths and can also detect presence of a cycle as well. So now question is, can we use Dynamic Programming to save work?
2) At each node, we can't simply store a single LCV value. Why? Well say we have this graph below and we're finding subproblem for node 2 (boxed): 
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b49037b9-265e-4a7c-a0c1-4c2b17b9ef3c_1635786388.7669652.png)
Now from #2's perspective, the LCV would be from path 2->3->4->5 and would be for color "B" and value would be 3 (node 3, node 4, node 5). But actually LCV for graph starts at node 0 and is 0->1->2->6 and is for color "R" and value is actually 4 (node 0, node 1, node 2, node 6). So when computing subproblem for node 2, we incorrectly discarded 2->6 path. We lost some information because color B "dominated" color R. So we need to store more information at each node. Hopefully this is motivation that we should add a color channel as well. This is now sufficient (One way to convince yourself is thinking about reduce the question to finding LCV but for 1 specfic color only).See ```nodeToColorToVal``` subproblem in my code. ```nodeToColorToVal.get(node).get(color)``` gives LCV over all paths starting at that ```node``` for that ```color```. To determine ```nodeToColorToVal.get(node)```, we would need to compute ```nodeToColorToVal.get(child)``` over all children. For each ```color```, cosider node's color and max over all children's  ```nodeToColorToVal.get(child).get(color)```. So we've recursively defined subproblem of a node in terms of it's children, which is how DFS works.

So putting everything together, DFS is just screaming to be used. It can detect cycle and it gives us a way to order solving subproblems.

