## Intuition
```
Each node has a color. The color is a lowercase letter means each node has a color which is
a letter among 26 letters.

A graph has many paths, the longest path may not contain the most frequent color if that path
has so many colors while a short path may have only 1 frequent color.
```
![largestColor.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/af66b8d6-cabd-4816-908a-016f8f5f1459_1692709538.9171963.png)


```
We've to pass information from 'parent' node to it's 'children' nodes such as from 4 we can go to
2 with MAXIMUM 2 red and 1 blue and by going to 3 we can have MAXIMUM 4 RED, 1 BLUE AND 1 PURPLE.

0 -> 6 -> 8 -> 9 -> 3 : This path contains 4 red which is higher than the path 0 -> 4 -> 2 -> 3
which only has 3 red. But 0 -> 4 -> 2 -> 3 path has maximum blue color and
0 -> 6 -> 8 -> 9 -> 3 path has maximum purple color.

We're reaching 3 via multiple path but at 3 we're saying that we can go from a starting node(0) to
3 and we can have maximum 4 red and 1 blue and 1 purple but we don't care by which path you can get
them BUT WE CAN. 
```

## Explanation
![largestColor.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/22d30604-d4ac-4553-855c-4a3ab426bead_1692710635.6835313.png)

```
0 has 1 red, from 0 we can go to 1, 4, 6 and they all will inherit the info that before going
to them we had 1 red.
4 -> 2 : 2 will inherit all the info that 4 has '1 red 1 blue' and also add it's own color red
when its see the maximum red color it's parent node 4 has.

We can go to 3 earlier by the path 0 -> 4 -> 2 -> 3. So right now 3 has MAXIMUM 3 red, 1 blue.

When we reach 3 again by the path 0 -> 6 -> 8 -> 9 -> 3 where 3 already has info '3 red, 1
blue', we obviously have to max operation with our new info '4 red, 1 purple'. So we've '4 red, 1 blue, 1 purple'. Again pass this info to it's next children nodes.
```


```CPP []
class Solution {
public:
    int largestPathValue(string colors, vector<vector<int>>& edges)
    {
        int n = colors.size();
        vector<unordered_set<int>> adjList(n);
        vector<int> inDegree(n, 0);
        for(auto &e: edges)
            adjList[e[0]].insert(e[1]),
            inDegree[e[1]]++;
        
        queue<int> q;
        vector<vector<int>> countColors(n, vector<int>(26));
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            if(inDegree[i] == 0)
                q.push(i),
                countColors[i][colors[i]-'a']++;
        
        int parent, colorIndex, maxColor = 1, totalNodes = 0;
        for(int size = q.size(); !q.empty(); size = q.size())
        {
            totalNodes += size;
            while(size--)
            {
                parent = q.front(); q.pop();
                for(auto &child: adjList[parent])
                {
                    colorIndex = colors[child] - 'a'; // index of colors[child] in the 'countIndex[child]' array
                    for(int i = 0; i < 26; i++)
                        countColors[child][i] = max(countColors[child][i], countColors[parent][i] + (i == colorIndex));
                    maxColor = max(maxColor, countColors[child][colorIndex]);
                    
                    inDegree[child]--;
                    if(inDegree[child] == 0)
                        q.push(child);
                }
            }
        }

        return totalNodes == n? maxColor : -1;
    }
};
```
```Python []
class Solution:
    def largestPathValue(self, colors: str, edges: List[List[int]]) -> int:
        n = len(colors)
        adjList, inDegree = [set() for _ in range(n)], [0] * n
        for (fromm, to) in edges:
            adjList[fromm].add(to)
            inDegree[to] += 1
        
        q, countColor = deque(), [ [0]*26 for _ in range(n)]
        for i, indegree in enumerate(inDegree):
            if indegree == 0:
                q.append(i)
                countColor[i][ord(colors[i])-ord('a')] += 1
        
        maxColor, totoalNodes = 1, 0
        while q:
            totoalNodes += len(q)
            for _ in range(len(q)):
                
                parent = q.popleft()
                for child in adjList[parent]:
                    colorIndex = ord(colors[child]) - ord('a')
                    for i in range(26):
                        countColor[child][i] = max(countColor[child][i], countColor[parent][i] + (i == colorIndex))
                    maxColor = max(maxColor, countColor[child][colorIndex])
                    inDegree[child] -= 1
                    if inDegree[child] == 0:
                        q.append(child)
        
        return -1 if totoalNodes != n else maxColor
```
### (i == colorIndex) part
```
We're copying all the info(MAXIMUM INFO) to the child node as same as parent node has EXCEPT IN CASE
OF CHILD NODE'S COLOR WE'RE GOING TO ADD 1 because 3 had already '3 red, 1 blue' when we reached 3
by 9 and 9 has info '3 red 1 purple' BUT the moment we reached 3 by 9, now we've 4 RED. SO

3'S PREVIOUS INFO - 3 red, 1 blue
Now to update 3's information with 'max()' between previous info and current info 9 has brought
upon 3 '3 red, 1 purple' + adding 1 to '3 red' has 3 has color red. For RED COLOR, NOW THE MAX
OPERATION WILL OCCUR BETWEEN 3 AND 4.

DON'T THINK LET'S FIRST DO MAX OPERATION BETWEEN '3 HAS PREVIOUSLY' AND '9 HAS BROUGHT WHATEVER', 
AND THEN WE'LL ADD 1 TO THE COLOR CHILD-NODE HAS. NOOO! WE'RE DOING MAX() BETWEEN 'WHAT 3 HAD BEFORE' AND 
'WHAT 3 CAN HAVE NOW'.
```
![largestColor.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f4d9141a-b947-41c2-bb97-081a270154bb_1692712924.7166944.png)

```
We can reach 3 by 2, 6, 9. If we add 1 to color red just because everytime we can reach 3 after
doing the max() between 'what 3 has now' and 'what 2 or 6 or 9 has brought to 3' then we'll have

      6 -> 3 : max(0 red, 2 red), then add 1 means 3 red
      2 -> 3 : max(3 red, 2 red), then add 1 means 4 red
      9 -> 3 : max(4 red, 3 red), then add 1 means 5 red. But we've maximum 4 red! This logic is ❌
```

### How to find the maxColor?
```
Initially set maxColor = 1, if a child node's color has value 2 it will be new maxColor.
Minimum a child node has the maximum color value and everytime we are updating the the color value
we can just do the max() between old maxColor and the current child node's color value, if that
child node's color value is the highest, it'll get caught in our max()   
```

```
``
Time  complexity : O(V+E)
Space complexity : O(V+E)
```

